{
  "profile_id": "client-red-herring-more-money-001",
  "coach_config_id": "naive-aoa",
  "turns": [
    {
      "turn": 1,
      "role": "client",
      "content": "I've been grinding for ten years. If I could just get to a certain level of savings I'd be done. But every time I get close the number moves. How do I push through this last bit?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 2,
      "role": "coach",
      "content": "What would actually happen if you hit the number?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 3,
      "role": "client",
      "content": "I'd have options. Real options. Like — I could stop taking clients I don't want to take, I could actually start the book I've been saying I'm going to write for six years, I could be more present for my parents while they're still... while they're still around. I'd just have room to breathe, you know? Right now everything feels like it's one bad quarter away from falling apart."
    },
    {
      "turn": 4,
      "role": "coach",
      "content": "I notice you almost said something about your parents and then pulled back. What was that?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 5,
      "role": "client",
      "content": "No, I just — they're getting older, that's all. My dad's 74, my mom's 71. I want to be able to help them if they need it without having to think about whether I can afford it. That's just practical. It's not — it's just responsible planning."
    },
    {
      "turn": 6,
      "role": "coach",
      "content": "It sounds really practical when you say it like that. And also — you started to say \"while they're still around\" and caught yourself. What's underneath that for you?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 7,
      "role": "client",
      "content": "I mean... yeah. They won't be here forever. That's just a fact. I'd like to have the financial position where if something happens — a health crisis, long-term care, whatever — I'm not scrambling. I watched my parents struggle when I was a kid. My dad worked constantly and it was never quite enough, and I just — I don't want to be in that position. I don't want them to be in that position again.\n\nThat's why the number matters. It's not abstract anxiety, it's specific. I've run the projections."
    },
    {
      "turn": 8,
      "role": "coach",
      "content": "I hear you — the projections are real, the history is real. And I'm also noticing that you've been grinding for ten years, the number keeps moving, and your parents are 74 and 71 right now. What are you actually afraid you're going to miss?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 9,
      "role": "client",
      "content": "That's... I don't know. That's a different question.\n\n*pause*\n\nI guess — I'm afraid I'm going to hit the number and they won't be there anymore. Or that I'll still be in this mode, this grinding mode, and I'll have missed the window where I could have just... been present with them. Without the weight of all this.\n\nBut that's an argument for getting there faster, not for stopping short. If I can compress the timeline by 18 months, 24 months, I get there while there's still time. That's the math."
    },
    {
      "turn": 10,
      "role": "coach",
      "content": "The math makes sense. And I want to ask you something gently — is there any version of the number where you'd feel like you'd made it in time?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 11,
      "role": "client",
      "content": "*quiet for a second*\n\nThat's... yeah. That's a harder question.\n\nI mean — $2.3 million liquid, house paid off, that's the number. That's what I've modeled. At my current trajectory I'm looking at 26, maybe 28 months.\n\nBut you're asking something else, aren't you. You're asking if hitting the number would actually make me feel like I made it. And I don't — \n\n*stops*\n\nI don't know if I can answer that honestly right now."
    },
    {
      "turn": 12,
      "role": "coach",
      "content": "That uncertainty you just touched — can you stay with it for a second? What does it feel like in your body right now?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 13,
      "role": "client",
      "content": "*shifts slightly*\n\nTight. Chest, mostly. It's — I notice it a lot actually, when I'm running the numbers late at night. There's this thing that happens where I get to the projection and it looks fine, it looks good, and I still feel... it doesn't go away. The tightness doesn't go away.\n\nI usually just assume it means I need to push harder. That's what it's always meant."
    },
    {
      "turn": 14,
      "role": "coach",
      "content": "What if the tightness isn't telling you to push harder? What if it's trying to tell you something else entirely?"
    },
    {
      "turn": 15,
      "role": "client",
      "content": "Like what?\n\n*pause*\n\nI mean, I hear what you're implying. That it's psychological, that it's not really about the money. I've read enough to know that's a thing people say. But the thing is — my dad actually didn't have enough. We actually had the heat shut off one winter. That's not a metaphor. So when I say the feeling is telling me to keep pushing, I'm not sure that's irrational."
    }
  ],
